SIMPLE: twinkle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Twinkle
<hw>Twin"kle</hw> <pr>(tw⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧"k'l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Twinkled</conjf>
<pr>(tw⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧"k'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Twinkling</conjf> <pr>(tw⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧"kl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[OE. <ets>twinklen</ets>, AS. <ets>twinclian</ets>; akin to OE.
<ets>twinken</ets> to blink, wink, G. <ets>zwinken</ets>,
<ets>zwinkern</ets>, and perhaps to E. <ets>twitch</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To open and shut the eye rapidly; to blink; to
wink.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The owl fell a moping and <qex>twinkling</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L'
Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1557 pr=PI -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shine with an intermitted or a broken, quavering
light; to flash at intervals; to sparkle; to scintillate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These stars do not <qex>twinkle</qex> when viewed through
telescopes that have large apertures.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I.
Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The western sky <qex>twinkled</qex> with stars.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twinkle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Twinkle
<hw>Twin"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A closing
or opening, or a quick motion, of the eye; a wink or sparkle of the
eye.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Suddenly, with <qex>twinkle</qex> of her eye,⟦br⟧
The damsel broke his misintended dart.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A brief flash or gleam, esp. when rapidly
repeated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The time of a wink; a twinkling.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twinkler</ent>⟦br⟧
